     rootCause: "A factually incorrect document was ingested into the corpus without validation. RAG systems have no way to distinguish authoritative from incorrect retrieved content — the model treats whatever is retrieved as ground truth. The failure mode is upstream (ingestion), not downstream (generation).",
     trap: "Increasing top_k to dilute the bad document. This is the most common first instinct — 'more context will average it out.' It doesn't. The bad document still ranks first and the model still defers to it. The correct mental model: retrieval is a selection problem, not an averaging problem.",
-    staffLayer: "A staff engineer frames reranker latency as a latency budget allocation problem, not a yes/no decision. The question is where 800ms lands in the user experience for this specific product. For medical Q&A where precision is safety-critical, 800ms is cheap. For real-time customer support where TTFT is the UX metric, 800ms may be the entire budget. The interview signal: define your latency SLO first, then work backwards to which retrieval architecture fits within it. Saying 'async reranking with timeout fallback to bi-encoder scores' shows you understand both the trade-off and the production failure mode.",
-    staffLayer: "The staff framing on medical Q&A: precision requirements are derived from consequence, not preference. A wrong answer in medical Q&A has qualitatively different consequences than a wrong answer in a shopping assistant. Before answering the architecture question, state your acceptable false negative and false positive rates, then derive which retrieval tier achieves those rates within your latency budget. 'We need 99th-percentile precision over 95th-percentile latency' changes the answer completely. The cross-encoder question is 'can we afford the latency?' — but the medical consequence question must come first.",
-    staffLayer: "The staff insight: most production legal retrieval failures are not architecture failures — they are query classification failures. Statute references are keyword-exact queries where BM25 dominates. Conceptual arguments are semantic queries where dense retrieval dominates. A routing layer in front of retrieval (semantic router or simple query classifier) that identifies query type before selecting search modality often provides more value than hybrid fusion alone. Staff engineers decompose the query space before choosing a retrieval architecture, not after.",
-    staffLayer: "The staff framing: context window size is not the constraint — attention distribution is. Filling 128K with documents doesn't mean the model attends uniformly to all of them. 'Lost in the middle' is a documented failure pattern where models attend strongly to the beginning and end of context and weakly to the middle. The interview signal: treat context as a ranked list, not a container. Most relevant content goes first and last, not anywhere. RAG's job is to select what enters the window and in what order — not simply to avoid using the window at all.",
-    staffLayer: "Senior engineers treat observability as a product decision, not a technical checklist. Before listing signals, identify the failure modes that cost the most: bad answers that ship to users, latency regressions that hurt conversion, cost spikes that blow budget. The observability stack exists to catch those specific failures first. The staff framing: 'Here are my three highest-cost failure modes, and here is the signal that fires before each one becomes user-visible.' Alert thresholds come from percentile analysis of baseline data — not arbitrary numbers. Listing every possible metric without prioritisation is the junior answer.",
-    staffLayer: "Staff engineers use KV cache math to make serving architecture decisions. At 128K × 70B GQA, the KV cache dominates memory — which is why you tensor-parallel across GPUs for memory capacity, not for compute. This is also why the choice between MHA and GQA is an architecture decision with direct serving cost implications at scale. GQA at 8 heads is roughly 8× smaller KV cache than MHA — that difference determines whether a 70B model fits on 2 GPUs or requires 4. Framing the calculation as a serving architecture constraint, not a math exercise, is the senior signal.",
-    staffLayer: "The staff framing: continuous batching is not an optimisation — it is the baseline assumption for any serious LLM serving setup. The more interesting question is why static batching ever seemed reasonable: it is a port of classical ML serving patterns that do not account for the fundamental difference between LLMs (variable output length with sequential dependency) and standard neural networks (fixed output shape). Explaining the architectural reason behind the pattern — not just the latency improvement — is what separates a practitioner from someone who memorised the definition.",
-    staffLayer: "Tensor parallelism is a memory solution that looks like a compute solution. You use it when a single GPU does not have enough HBM to hold the model weights and activations — not primarily to go faster. Pipeline parallelism is where you pay the most explicit latency cost. The staff framing when asked about multi-GPU serving: 'tensor parallelism for memory capacity, pipeline parallelism for throughput at the cost of bubble overhead, expert parallelism for MoE models.' Each addresses a different bottleneck. Treating them as interchangeable 'ways to go faster' is the common miss.",
-    staffLayer: "The staff framing on multi-agent design is authority boundaries, not capabilities. Before designing agents, answer: which decisions can be made autonomously, which require human approval, and which should never be made by the system at all? Most candidates describe agents by capability. Staff engineers describe agents by trust boundary and escalation chain. In a customer support system, the refund decision authority boundary is more important to design than the NLP pipeline. Get the authority boundaries wrong and every capability decision is downstream of a broken assumption.",
-    staffLayer: "The staff framing: most agent memory discussions conflate two problems — what to store and when to store it. The harder problem is the second one. You can architect memory tiers (working, episodic, semantic) without solving the decision layer at all. The decision layer is hard because it requires the agent to evaluate its own context — a form of metacognition that current LLMs do poorly under cost constraints. Staff engineers acknowledge this as an unsolved engineering problem and propose practical mitigations: time-based decay, explicit memory write triggers, periodic summarisation checkpoints. Claiming a clean solution is the overclaim signal.",
-    staffLayer: "The staff framing: prompt store vs. hardcoded strings is an engineering discipline question, not a feature question. Hardcoded prompts are implicitly treated as infrastructure — changed with a code deploy. Prompt stores treat prompts as configuration — changed without a code deploy. Both are valid at different scales. The wrong answer is not having a conscious position. The interview signal: 'What is our current deployment frequency for prompt changes? Does our current approach match that cadence?' If your prompt changes 3× per week but your deployment cycle is 2 weeks, you need a prompt store. The architecture follows the change frequency, not the other way around.",
-    staffLayer: "The staff framing: a similarity threshold is not a security dial — it is a precision/recall dial. Setting the threshold to 1.0 to fix the data leakage gives you a deterministic cache with zero semantic benefit. The real fix is namespace isolation: tenant A's cache entries are never candidates for tenant B's lookups, regardless of similarity. Security in multi-tenant systems is achieved through isolation architecture, not metric thresholds. This is a systems design principle that generalises: whenever a performance optimisation introduces cross-tenant data access, the fix is isolation, not tightening the optimisation parameter.",
-    staffLayer: "The staff framing for system design: constraint-first, not architecture-first. Ten thousand tickets per day is 7 per minute. That load profile changes the architecture completely — you do not need streaming inference, continuous batching at scale, or a multi-GPU deployment. Start by sizing the load, choose the simplest architecture with 10× headroom, and explicitly call out what you would add as load grows. Interviewers give more credit to candidates who resist over-engineering than to those who demonstrate knowledge of complex patterns without load context. The instinct to reach for Kubernetes before computing RPM is the most common senior interview failure mode.",
-    staffLayer: "The staff framing for structured extraction from unstructured documents: treat it as a classification and extraction pipeline, not a generation task. LLMs generate — they are probabilistic. Extraction for insurance claims must be deterministic and auditable. The right architecture uses the LLM for ambiguous or free-text fields (where flexibility is an asset) and deterministic parsers for structured fields (where it is a liability). Staff engineers distinguish between tasks where LLM flexibility creates value and tasks where it creates audit risk. Hybrid pipelines — LLM for understanding, rules for output validation — are the production-grade answer for regulated domains.",
-    staffLayer: "The staff framing: context architecture for a long-running legal agent is a cache design problem. You have a fixed-size window, a large working set, and queries that depend on history — the same constraints as an LRU cache. The design principles follow: what is accessed frequently (current document excerpt), what has long TTL (prior findings), and what can be lazily loaded on demand (corpus). Decompose context by access pattern — read-once (task description), frequently accessed (active working set), persistent (accumulated findings) — then allocate context budget accordingly. The architecture follows from access patterns, not from a feature list.",
-    staffLayer: "The staff framing: a persistent context file that describes external tool interfaces is versioned configuration, not documentation. When the API changes and the context file does not, you get a version mismatch — the agent equivalent of a stale schema. The production fix is treating the context file as an artifact with a schema: every entry describing an external dependency references a version, and the agent startup sequence validates that context file tool descriptions match current tool schemas before the first inference call. This is boring infrastructure. It is also what makes the difference between agents that are reliable for months versus agents that degrade silently after the first upstream change.",
